Configuration & Logging Demo
Overview

This project demonstrates how Configuration and Logging work in ASP.NET Core using:

appsettings.json for configuration

Custom logging service (ILogService)

Dependency Injection

Controller actions

The application reads App Name and Version from configuration and logs controller activity to the console.

Configuration

Configuration values are stored in appsettings.json.

Example:

{
  "AppInfo": {
    "AppName": "Configuration Demo App",
    "Version": "1.0"
  }
}

These values are accessed using IConfiguration.

Example:

var appName = config["AppInfo:AppName"];
var version = config["AppInfo:Version"];

This allows the application to manage settings without modifying code.

Logging

A custom logging service is used to track application activity.

ILogService

public interface ILogService
{
    void Log(string message);
}

LogService

public class LogService : ILogService
{
    public LogService()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("[Service] LogService Instance Created");
    }

    public void Log(string message)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"[Service] {message}");
    }
}

The service is registered using Dependency Injection.

builder.Services.AddSingleton<ILogService, LogService>();
Controller Example
[HttpGet("index")]
public IActionResult Index()
{
    var appName = config["AppInfo:AppName"];
    var version = config["AppInfo:Version"];

    logService.Log("DemoController.Index Executed");

    return Content($"Welcome to {appName} - Version {version}");
}
